                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1014">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.711/74: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-08T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 8, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:58 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1878. For Dunn<note n="1" xml:id="d1014fn1">James Clement Dunn, Director of the
                        Office of European Affairs.</note> from Phillips.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d1014fn2">William Phillips, Political Adviser at the Headquarters of
                        the Supreme Allied Commander, London.</note> It would be helpful in dealing
                    with questions involving censorship control in liberated areas if I might be
                    informed whether such censorship should be used solely as a military measure or
                    might be broadened in scope to include such matters as trade information, etc.,
                    for use in the post war period. My personal understanding is that it should be
                    used only as a military expedient but I should appreciate receiving the
                    Department’s views. [Phillips.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
